  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "9a1vB2X06srB7gjSrfNM/AUfK1c=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "The current Powerhouse default sync path creates 2x duplication by design:\n\n```\nCONNECT (browser)                    SWITCHBOARD (server)\nPGlite (local)                       PostgreSQL (remote)\n  - operations                         - operations (SAME data)\n  - documents                          - documents\n  - relationships                      - relationships\n\nSyncManager                          SyncManager\n  outbox -> GqlRequestChannel -----> inbox -> reactor.load()\n  inbox  <- GqlRequestChannel <----- outbox\n```\n\n**Every operation exists in BOTH databases.** The SyncManager on each side moves `SyncEnvelope` payloads across the `GqlRequestChannel`, ensuring eventual consistency.\n\nThe Switchboard is the authoritative remote \u2014 a server someone runs. This is the baseline duplication everything else is compared against. It's not a bug or inefficiency; it's the cost of having a multi-device-sync-capable remote copy.\n\nThis 2x pattern is the yardstick: any alternative sync path (Swarm, Swarm+Switchboard, fully decentralized) inherits or exceeds it.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
